// 03c-data-fuel-specific — Fuel-Specific Data

=== AFRL Jet Fuel Property Compilation <afrl-data>

The primary source of fuel-mixture ground truth in this work is the AFRL technical report AFRL-RQ-WP-TR-2020-0017, authored by Edwards and published in January 2020 @Edwards2020. This 136-page document constitutes the most comprehensive publicly available compilation of thermophysical properties for both conventional petroleum-derived and alternative jet fuels. Edwards catalogues properties for three Category A reference fuels---JP-8 (POSF 10264), Jet-A (POSF 10325), and JP-5 (POSF 10289)---alongside more than ten alternative fuels, including Shell SPK (POSF 5729), Sasol IPK (POSF 7629), Syntroleum S-8 (POSF 5018), UOP camelina HEFA (POSF 10301), Gevo ATJ (POSF 11498), and several others. Each fuel is identified by its POSF (Properties of Fuels) tracking number, a unique integer assigned by the AFRL Fuels and Energy Branch to every fuel sample that enters the characterization pipeline.

The report is distributed as thirteen CSV files, each corresponding to a different property or property class. Tabulated quantities include density, dynamic viscosity, surface tension, speed of sound, bulk modulus, lubricity, distillation curves, derived cetane number, flash point, freeze point, net heat of combustion, hydrogen content, and molecular weight distributions. Temperature-dependent data are provided where available: density--temperature linear equations derived from the CRC Handbook and the Department of Defense World Fuel Survey, viscosity at $-20 degree.c$ and $-40 degree.c$, and surface tension as a function of temperature with linear-fit coefficients. Detailed GC$times$GC hydrocarbon-class composition breakdowns enable composition-weighted property modeling of real fuel mixtures. Of particular value to this work are the low-temperature viscosity measurements for alternative fuels, the surface tension linear regressions, and the GC$times$GC composition data that supply the mole fractions needed to aggregate pure-compound predictions into fuel-level estimates.

Six fuels from the Edwards compilation serve as the validation set throughout Phases 3 and 4 of this study. @fuel-validation-table summarizes these fuels together with the POSF identifiers and measured property ranges used for model evaluation.

